    <text>
        <front/>
        <body>
            <pb n="1" facs="#f0001"/>
            <dateline>
                <hi rendition="#et">LONDON, Oct 17.</hi>
            </dateline>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">extent and population of america.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The following estimate of the extent,<lb break="yes"/>in square leagues, and population, of the<lb break="yes"/>Continent of America in 1822, was late-<lb break="no"/>ly transmitted by Baron de Humboldt<lb break="yes"/>from Paris, to President Bolivar, with<lb break="yes"/>the accompanying letter:</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2"/>
                        <cell>Sqr. Leagues</cell>
                        <cell>Population</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Mexico or New Spain</cell>
                        <cell>75,830</cell>
                        <cell>6,800 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Guatemala</cell>
                        <cell>16,740</cell>
                        <cell>1,600 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Cuba and Puerto Rico</cell>
                        <cell>4,430</cell>
                        <cell>800 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell rows="2" rendition="#rightBraced">Colombia</cell>
                        <cell>Venezuela</cell>
                        <cell>33,700</cell>
                        <cell>900 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell>N. Grenada</cell>
                        <cell>58 230</cell>
                        <cell>1,800 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Peru</cell>
                        <cell>42,150</cell>
                        <cell>1,400 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Chili</cell>
                        <cell>14,240</cell>
                        <cell>1,100 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Buenos Ayres</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rendition="#u">126,770</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rendition="#u">2,000 000</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Total formerly Spanish</cell>
                        <cell>372,110</cell>
                        <cell>16,400 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">United States</cell>
                        <cell>125 440</cell>
                        <cell>10,200 000</cell>
                    </row>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <row>
                        <cell cols="2">Brazil</cell>
                        <cell>256 990</cell>
                        <cell>4,000 000</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The above surfaces have been calculat-<lb break="no"/>ed with great care, on maps rectified by<lb break="yes"/>astronomical observations. The calenla-<lb break="no"/>tions have been several times repeated by<lb break="yes"/>M. Mathieu, member of the Board of<lb break="yes"/>Longitude, as well as by myself. The<lb break="yes"/>results differ from those published in<lb break="yes" />1809, in the Political E@say on Mexico.<lb break="yes"/>Then the inhabited parts alone had been<lb break="yes"/>calculated, withont including the desert<lb break="yes"/>regions, over which the independent<lb break="yes"/>tribes of the indegenous inhabitants wan-<lb break="no"/>der. Now the whole extent of each<lb break="yes"/>country, to its furthest limits, has been<lb break="yes"/>measured.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The population of the different parts<lb break="yes"/>of <hi rendition="#i" >ci-devant</hi> Spanish America is very un-<lb break="no"/>certain, nevertheless each portion has<lb break="yes"/>been calculated according to the latest<lb break="yes"/>data which have reached me. The pre-<lb break="no" />sent estimate ought to be considered in<lb break="yes"/>the same light as all my other works on<lb break="yes"/>America; they are no other than essa@s,<lb break="yes"/>@ will have to be done<lb break="yes"/>over again. Statistical calculations can<lb break="yes"/>only be rendere@ perfect by deg@ in<lb break="yes"/>like manner as the elements of meteoro-<lb break="no"/>logical and astronomical tables.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Comparison.</hi>&#x2014;Spain contains 16,094<lb break="yes" />square leagné@&#x2014;Europe contains 304,710<lb break="yes"/>square leagues, and the whole of South-<lb break="no"/>ern America 581,891 square leagues.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">(Signed) HUMBOLDT.</hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
